Here's a recommended approach:

**1. Abstract the HTTP dependency**

```csharp
// Use IHttpClientFactory or inject HttpClient via constructor
public class WeatherTool(HttpClient httpClient)
{
    public async Task<string> GetWeatherAsync(string city)
    {
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/api/weather/{city}");
        return response;
    }
}
```

**2. Create the test project**

```bash
dotnet new xunit -n MyMcpServer.Tests
cd MyMcpServer.Tests
dotnet add reference ../MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj
dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Http
dotnet add package RichardSzalay.MockHttp   # popular mock HTTP handler
```

**3. Test with a mock HTTP handler**

```csharp
using RichardSzalay.MockHttp;

public class WeatherToolTests
{
    [Fact]
    public async Task GetWeather_ReturnsExpectedData()
    {
        // Arrange — fake the external API
        var mockHttp = new MockHttpMessageHandler();
        mockHttp
            .When("/api/weather/Seattle")
            .Respond("application/json", """{"temp": 55}""");

        var client = mockHttp.ToHttpClient();
        client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");

        var tool = new WeatherTool(client);

        // Act
        var result = await tool.GetWeatherAsync("Seattle");

        // Assert
        Assert.Contains("55", result);
    }
}
```

**Key structural points:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **Inject `HttpClient`** | Constructor injection; avoids `new HttpClient()` inside tools |
| **Mock layer** | `MockHttpMessageHandler` (or hand-roll a `DelegatingHandler`) |
| **Project layout** | `src/MyMcpServer/` + `tests/MyMcpServer.Tests/` |
| **No real calls** | The mock handler intercepts all requests — nothing hits the network |

If you prefer zero dependencies, you can write your own stub handler:

```csharp
class StubHandler : HttpMessageHandler
{
    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage req, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var response = new HttpResponseMessage(System.Net.HttpStatusCode.OK)
        {
            Content = new StringContent("""{"temp": 55}""")
        };
        return Task.FromResult(response);
    }
}
```

The critical design rule: **never `new` up `HttpClient` inside your tool classes** — always inject it so tests can substitute a fake.
